ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we deposited amino-functionalized GQDs-doped PDA layer on the surface of plasma-sprayed HAp coating (GQD/PDA-HAp) (Scheme 1
                     ). The ROS scavenging activities of the coatings were investigated using ABTS·+, DPPH and O2
                     ·- free radicals. The antioxidant effects of the amino-functionalized GQDs and the PDA layer were confirmed. The synergistic antioxidant mechanism of the GQD/PDA-HAp coating was unveiled through investigating the effect of amino-functionalized GQDs on the catechol structure and the redox-activity of PDA. Protective effects of the GQD/PDA-HAp coating on the functions of MC3T3-E1 osteoblasts against ROS-induced oxidative stress was studied.

Since the antioxidant performance of PDA was inextricably linked to the amount of its catechol structure, the catechol content in the coatings was measured by using Folin colorimetric assay[20]. Quantitative results in Fig. 5
                        A showed that the GQD/PDA-HAp coating had a larger absorbance value than the PDA-HAp coating, indicating higher catechol content. It suggested that the cross-linking of the amino-functionalized GQDs with the PDA might protect catechol groups in dopamine monomer from oxidation during the self-polymerization process. The oxygen atomic percentage (Table 1
                        ) and the C=O content (Fig. 5B) of the PDA layer increased significantly after oxidation in air, while a slight increase was observed for the GQD/PDA layer. This demonstrated that the presence of the amino-functionalized GQDs could inhibit the oxidation of GQD/PDA layer in air. Wang et al.[41] reported that the mechanisms of free radical scavenging of PDA mainly include hydrogen atom transfer (HAT) and single electron transfer (SET) in catechol, which provides H or releases electrons. Increasing the catechol content in PDA could enhance its ROS scavenging ability.
